      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. B. Organizing</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option B:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The <strong>approach to management</strong>, which <strong>focuses on unity</strong> of <strong>direction</strong> and <strong>unity of command</strong>, <strong>aligns closely</strong> with the principle of <strong>&#39;Organizing&#39; in management theory</strong>. <strong>Organizing</strong> involves <strong>arranging the resources</strong> (including human resources) of an organization in such a way that they effectively and efficiently work towards the organization&#39;s goals. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Principles of Organizing&nbsp;-&nbsp;</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type:lower-roman\">\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Unity of direction</span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: One leader &amp; one plan for a group of activities having the same objectives.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Unity of command:&nbsp;</span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">A subordinate report only one boss to avoid conflict of orders.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Authority</span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: Every individual in an organization has some responsibility commensurate with his authority.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Span of control</span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: Number of subordinates supervised by a leader should not be too many for better control.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Flexibility</span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: Organizational staffing pattern &amp; structure should be able to accommodate changes in internal &amp; external environments.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Management by exception</span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: All routine decisions should be taken by subordinates &amp; only policy decisions and unusual matters should be referred to the leader.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Scalar principle</span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: Clear lines of authority in hierarchical structure ensures more effective performance.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation -&nbsp;</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option&nbsp;A.&nbsp;</span></strong><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Planning</span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: Involves <strong>defining goals</strong> and <strong>outlining strategies</strong> to <strong>achieve them</strong>, but does not specifically address the structure of supervision and team alignment.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option&nbsp;C.&nbsp;</span></strong><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Staffing</span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: Pertains to the <strong>recruitment, training</strong>, and <strong>development of staff</strong>, and does not directly relate to the principles of unity of direction and command.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option</span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">&nbsp;<strong>D.</strong> <strong>Directing</strong>: Involves <strong>leading and motivating employees</strong> to <strong>achieve organizational objectives</strong>, but is broader than the specific focus on team structure and unified objectives.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Organizing&nbsp;</span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">is key to establishing <strong>efficient operational structures</strong> in <strong>management</strong>, characterized by <strong>clear command lines</strong> and <strong>unified direction</strong>.&nbsp;The <strong>unity of direction</strong> ensures that <strong>all team members</strong> are <strong>working</strong> towards the <strong>same objectives</strong>, while the <strong>unity of command</strong> ensures that each <strong>team member</strong> has only <strong>one direct supervisor</strong>, thereby streamlining decision-making and reducing confusion. This principle is essential for establishing clear lines of authority and responsibilities within a team or organization</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: AFMC textbook, Pg 316</span></strong></span></span></p>",
